Hint 1
Try some special cases, such as $$$r=c=2$$$, $$$n=r$$$, or $$$m=c$$$, etc.
Solution
In terms of systems of equations, the given problem fixes for us the parities of at most (and exactly) $$$(n-r+1)\cdot(m-c+1)$$$ cells (by giving us a system of equations to solve with that many equations). What this means is that, if we are to fill an upper border of thickness $$$r-1$$$ and a left border of thickness of $$$c-1$$$, then every cell from that point onward is determined uniquely by some equation (Tip: imagine how this pans out for a $$$2\times2$$$ matrix; after filling the first row and left column arbitrarily, cell (2,2) is uniquely determined, then (2,3), and so on).
Therefore, the answer is $$$2^{nm - (n-r+1)(m-c+1)}$$$.
